Minstrels FAQ
Version 2.1
FAQ created 09 Feb 2000
This version 03 Mar 2006: miscellaneous updates and revisions.

1. Errm, what exactly is the Wondering Minstrels?
        The Wondering Minstrels is a poetry-by-email service run by Abraham
Thomas and Martin DeMello, with an accompanying archive website created and
maintained by Sitaram Iyer. Martin and Thomas (who prefers using his second
name) send a poem a day, (almost) every day, to everyone on the Minstrels
mailing list. Along with the poems we send personal commentaries, critical
analyses, poet biographies, historical asides, trivia, links - basically,
anything that catches our fancy. Sitaram archives these poems on the
Minstrels website, which also offers options for reader comments and
feedback, user-defined poem 'collections', links to random poems, and
various clever sort and search options. You can visit the archive at
		http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels/

[Update: the Minstrels has been on hiatus for a few months, but as of 01 Mar
2006 we're back in action, and look forward to resuming our regular service.
The Minstrels website has also been a bit iffy of late, but Sitaram is
working on getting it up and running again.]

2. Where did you get the name?
        "A Wandering Minstrel I
        A thing of shreds and patches
        Of ballads, songs and snatches
        And dreamy lullaby."
                -- W. S. Gilbert, 'The Mikado'
        Apart from being a tip of the hat to one of our favourite poets (in
one of his best snatches of verse), the pun on 'wondering-wandering' is
meant to evoke a sense of the numinous - truly great poetry takes you on a
journey of revelation and wonder, emotion and insight.

3. Who are you guys, anyway?
        Thomas is a bond trader who works for a hedge fund based in
Princeton, New Jersey. Martin is an open-source hacker and filker currently
working in Bangalore, India. Sitaram is a computer scientist who works for
everyone's favourite search engine, Google, in Mountain View, California. We
were all undergraduates at the Indian Institute of Technology (IIT) Bombay,
which is how we know each other.
        You can contact us directly at the following email addresses:
		<thomas@simplexasset.com>
		<martindemello@yahoo.com>
		<ssiyer@cs.rice.edu>
        Alternatively, you can send a single email to 
		<minstrels-owner@yahoogroups.com>
which should reach all three of us. 
		
4. Why do you do it?
        We've long felt that the average person didn't read (or re-read, for
that matter) nearly enough poetry. Minstrels is just our way of trying to
rectify the situation. Our goal is simple: if we can brighten up people's
days, make them think a little, make them feel a little, perhaps encourage
them to buy a book of poetry... well, if we can accomplish any of these
things, we'd be more than satisfied. 
        Another reason we keep up the show is to challenge the widely held
belief that modern poetry - indeed, 'serious' poetry of any sort - is
'hard', that it requires special skills and training to  appreciate. This is
simply not true, and it's our mission to demonstrate the fact.  
        Altruistic motives aside, the main reason we run Minstrels is that
it's fun. We enjoy writing our little commentaries and analyses every other
day. We love doing the research that goes into each Minstrels post -
learning more about poems, poets and poetry as a whole. We get a thrill out
of discovering new gems in the course of our browsing. But most of all, we
thrive on feedback from people like you, Gentle Reader: your criticism and
compliments, your likes and dislikes, your opinions of our choices and our
analyses, your views and reviews, your bouquets and brickbats - in short,
everything you send in. It's what keeps us going.

5. How do you choose your poems?
        Well, basically, we run poems that we like. Period. We do try to
include 'famous' and 'important' poems, but these criteria are secondary.
Fortunately, Martin and Thomas have sufficiently divergent tastes to prevent
matters from getting unduly monotonous; also, the mechanism of guest poems
(see below) balances things somewhat.

6. This poem sucks - why did you include it?
        Simple - one of us liked it :-) . But feel free to post a comment
(see Q11 below) with your view of the matter.

7. This poem is great - why haven't you included it?
        Perhaps neither of us liked it; perhaps it's on our to-do list;
perhaps it was just overlooked. In any case, we welcome suggestions and
requests. Even better, you could run it as a guest poem (see Q8 below).

8. What is a guest poem?
        In order to introduce a little more variety into our selections, and
to increase reader participation, we run guest poems a few times a week. If
you have a poem you'd like to share, just send it to either of us and we'll
forward it to the list. The criteria are simple: it should be a poem that
you think is enjoyable and/or noteworthy, and you should write a comment
saying why.
        The commentary needn't follow any particular pattern - we've had
everything from critical analysis to special memories associated with the
poem - but it is mandatory. We have found that the personal touch greatly
enhances the reader's experience of the poem, and we would like Minstrels to
be more than a mere transcription service.
        Ideally, copies of guest poems should be sent to all three of us;
that way we can ensure that none of them 'falls through the cracks', as it
were.

9. I'd love to submit a guest poem, but I can't do the critical analysis. 
        While we (Martin and Thomas) happen to enjoy critical analysis of
poetry, it is by no means the only way to appreciate a poem. Any sort of
comment is fine - if you're submitting a poem you obviously have some
reasons you think it's good; merely include those reasons.

9b. Or the biographical research.
        The biographical notes are an extra; if you can't manage them we'd
be glad to do so for you. Of course, every little bit you send in helps,
especially in the case of contemporary poets (who haven't made it into the
reference books yet). 

10. Do you accept original poetry from your guest submitters?
        No. We're anthologists rather than editors; our main purpose is to
introduce people to the large body of existing English (and translated)
poetry. There are several websites and mailing lists dedicated to publishing
and discussing original poetry; it's not too hard to find them using a
search engine.

11. Great poem and comments, but you left something out...
        That's what the comment mechanism is for. Either click the comment
link on the Minstrels website, or mail one of us your comments, and they'll
be added to the page. We'll also try to send out a compilation of each
month's comments to the list - think of it as a 'letters to the editor'
section.
        There's also an accompanying discussion group called MinstrelsD,
where list-members exchange occasional emails about the poems we run. If
you'd like to join, simply send a blank mail to 
		<minstrelsd-subscribe@yahoogroups.com>
MinstrelsD is moderated, which means that either Martin or Thomas has to
approve every message that gets posted on it. To send a message to
MinstrelsD, email
		<minstrelsd@yahoogroups.com>

12. Today's Minstrels email had a mistake in it. Can you fix it?
        With pleasure. Despite our best efforts at accuracy, some mistakes
go unspotted in our posts. These could be speling mistakes, punctuation and
formatting errors, even textual and factual goofs. We're very grateful to
all those readers who take the time and trouble to email us pointing these
out; and in each case we'll try to fix the archive as soon as possible.
(Though be warned that sometimes 'as soon as possible' can mean a delay of
several weeks, depending on where we are in the website maintenance cycle).

13. What are themes? And collections?
        Every now and then we decide to run (on the mailing list) a series
of poems linked by a common theme. These themes may be obvious (eg. "poems
about the sea", or "poems about cats"), or not so obvious (eg. "poems often
parodied", or "poems about places on the Silk Road"). Either way we think
they make Minstrels more fun :-). Occasionally our readers submit sets of
three or more guest poems linked by a commonality of some sort; we then run
these in sequence as a guest theme. And sometimes a reader sends in a poem
(or two) that was suggested to him or her by reading one of our posts, and
voila, a theme develops where none was planned. 
        Collections are a (fairly recent) feature of the website (not the
mailing list!), using which website visitors can define groups of poems
based on their own criteria; eg. "Sandy's favourite poems", or "Poems about
Food and Drink". These offer a way to sort and store specific subsets of the
Minstrels archive. Naturally, each theme we run is treated as one among
these subsets; readers are invited to define others. You can read more about
Minstrels collections at this URL: 
	http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels/etc/collections.html

14. I know someone who'd really love to be on Minstrels; how do I add
him/her to the list?
        Ask him/her to send a blank email to
<minstrels-subscribe@yahoogroups.com>. The automated mailing list manager at
yahoogroups will do the rest. 

15. I'd like to be taken off the list; how do I do it?
        You're not serious, are you? :-).
        Well, if you insist - send a blank mail to
<minstrels-unsubscribe@yahoogroups.com>. The automated mailing list manager
at yahoogroups will do the rest. 

16. I'd like to change the email address at which I receive the poems; how
do I do it?
        There are two steps to this. First, unsubscribe your OLD email
address by sending a blank email from that address to
<minstrels-unsubscribe@yahoogroups.com>. Next, subscribe your NEW email
address by sending a blank email from the new address to
<minstrels-subscribe@yahoogroups.com>. 

17. I joined the list a few days ago, but have yet to receive any poems / I
was getting the poems just fine until a few days ago, but since then,
nothing. What's going on?
        The first thing to do is to check if you really are missing poems;
it's possible that we haven't posted anything to the list in a few days.
(This happens rarely, but it does happen, especially when one or more of us
is travelling or otherwise busy). Go to the Minstrels website and compare
the latest poem there to the latest one in your inbox; if there's a
mismatch, then you're missing poems. 
        Next, check if there are any problems at your end. Are you failing
to receive other (ie, non-Minstrels) email? Is your mailbox full? Are you
running a (personal or institutional) spam filter that blocks Minstrels
posts? If the answers to any of these qusetions is "yes", you probably need
to contact your email system administrator.
        If you're missing poems and your email system is working fine, the
problem may lie with yahoogroups (the web service we use to manage the
mailing list). Sometimes the list manager program at yahoogroups classifies
email addresses as "bouncing" (ie, invalid), because they were temporarily
unavailable (due to full mailboxes, network outages, or a host of other
reasons). Unfortunately, the program does not automatically re-classify
("un-bounce") these addresses when their email problems are resolved. So you
may have to unsubscribe and resubscribe in order to force the program to
recognize the validity of your address. (See Q14 and Q15 for instructions on
how to unsubscribe and resubscribe. Be sure to wait for (say) an hour
between the two tasks to allow the program time to process your first
request). 
        If after all this you're still not getting your daily poetry fix,
email us, and we'll look into it.

18. I just joined the list a short time ago; is there any way I can get hold
of old poems?
        All our poems are archived at the Minstrels website, 
		http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels 
The website is powered by Sitaram's perl wizardry.

19. The website doesn't seem to be working, is there something wrong?
        Chances are, we're regenerating the web pages (or rather, Sitaram's
maintenance program is doing so). Wait for a bit, and then try again. If you
still can't get to the website, email us, and we'll look into it. Also, if
your browser displays the poems in a strange format, please let us know. 

[Update: As of today, 03 Mar 2006, the most recent poem sent to the mailing
list was #1814, by Tennyson. However, the most recent poem on the website is
#1812, by Hope. Sitaram is looking into this discrepancy, and should have it
fixed Real Soon Now].

20. How many people are there on the list?
        As of today, 03 Mar 2006, there are 4048 people on the Minstrels
mailing list. 

21. I have this homework assignment to do; can you help?
        Sorry, we can't provide you with an essay or additional notes. Feel
free to use the material already in our archives, though, as long as you
credit it properly. Also, if you have any specific questions, write in and
we'll do our best to answer them. Homework assistance is a tricky issue;
this website: 
	http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~martinh/poems/questions.html 
has a detailed explanation of some of the problems involved.

22. Will you ever release my email address to others? 
        Absolutely not. Addresses on the mailing list are completely
confidential. We've configured the mailserver so that only Martin, Sitaram
and Thomas can post to list members; furthermore, yahoogroups has a strict
anti-spamming policy in place, so there's an additional layer of protection.
Next, the list archives on the yahoogroups website are viewable by members
only, so spammers can't get at them. And finally, the program that generates
the Minstrels web pages is designed to strip out all email addresses, so you
needn't worry about your address being published on the website when you
send in a guest poem or a comment. We hate junk mail as much as you do.
        Incidentally, if you'd like to submit guest poems anonymously
(hiding your name, email address or both), let us know and we'll take care
of it. 

23. I love your website; can I add a link to it from my own home page?
        By all means. An email notifying us to that effect would also be
welcome (though it's not compulsory); we like to know who's pointing to us.

24. Are the poems on Minstrels in the public domain?
        Many of the poems on Minstrels date from the 19th century or before,
and hence are in the public domain. In the case of more recent poems, we
believe that our posts fall under the doctrine of "fair use", since we
present the poems mainly as starting points for commentary and discussions. 
        If you believe a poem should not be on our website for any reason,
please write to us explaining why, and we'd be glad to remove it. We respect
the right of poets to control their work; we also respect their right to
profit from the sale of poetry books. In the same spirit, we encourage list
members and web surfers to support the work of writers they admire by buying
their books. 

25. Can you ... ?
        If you have any suggestions on how we can improve the Wondering
Minstrels, do write in to <minstrels-owner@yahoogroups.com>.


To unsubscribe from this list, send a blank message to 
<minstrels-unsubscribe@yahoogroups.com>

